segments.text: I have the honor and pleasure of being with Mr. Sterling Evans at his hacienda out at Brackettville, and we're chatting about his recollections.
When did you learn you were the valedictorian?
And it was in Guyon Hall.
Was he the president at A&M then?
Do you have any recollections of him?
I'm going up to interview his daughter soon.
She is 95 and living up in Oklahoma City.
So I'm looking forward to interviewing her.
You became active in former student activities in the 1940s.
What led you to become active?
All right, we'll get it later.
And what were your first leadership, former student leadership activities?
I said, Governor, I do want girls to go left.
But I promise you, you'll appoint me.
Try to do a thing about it.
I said, I was right here.
So, I went ahead and appointed me.
I could have done it with the one next week.
I didn't do it because I promised him.
Anyway, we had to print this.
So he wanted to spend it.
Of course, John Brackett, I just wanted to send a thing to that kind of thing.
Who were your biggest allies on the board favoring co-education?
I wouldn't have done today than we did.
They said, why are we guilty?
Now, John Lindsay was the former student president?
So the president, he was former president.
Of course, anyway, he got over to John.
And John, he just got to get to John today.
And Dick Hervey helped him, didn't he?
Now, Mr. Zachary, was he on the board of directors with you then?
And let's see, was Al Davies, was he on the board yet?
When did you personally start favoring co-education?
Was there any event or anything that... What about making the Corps voluntary?
My brother came to it, and we asked for war when it was popular.
I said, boy, there's more to go in.
So he said, we got changed.
We always had a group at that time.
So he came to the board.
He said, we got to make changes.
He said, okay, what you want, my favorite.
Anyway, Rutter was a great fellow.
Now, you said a while ago, before we turned on the machine, that if you had been on the board when Mr. Rutter was selected, you might not have voted for him.
What do you know about college education?
Who was it, as far as you know, that identified Mr. Rutter to be the new president?
I believe as executive vice president.
Now, the fact that he was from the hill country, do you think that helped him any?
Now, he also knew John Connolly well.
And you knew Mr. Connolly well, did you not?
What about connections with President Johnson?
Was there ever any discussion about the admission of black students of racial integration?
Did anybody oppose it that you recall?
I have never heard of any opposition.
And Mr. Rudder handled that with great skill.
Do you remember any anecdotes or stories about Mr. Rutter that you can share?
One of the greatest friends in the university.
I particularly am grateful that he is so interested in the library because I share with you that interest.
What caused you to be interested in the library?
When I went to school, Tommy Mayo, the library, the good one, the color, the service.
You know, we're not the gentles of society.
He got the first ... There weren't something else he was the first, but he was a good man.
He was going to talk about it.
Who were some of the other faculty members when you were a student that had a very positive influence on you?
I remember, I prayed, what could you do?
I got to be good at his class.
He was a good one, too.
I worked like a different person.
And now you grew up, you went to high school in Uvalde.
Why did you go to A&M instead of some other school?
I couldn't have to put my soldiers out in the training.
I got to the University of Texas.
Did you ever visit A&M before you enrolled there?
Did you visit College Station before you went over there to enroll?
Did you go on the train?
I went over to the port of the station.
And then you were in College Station how long?
Did you spend the night there?
How many in your high school graduating class?
Now, at Uvalde High School, how many graduated when you did?
And about how many went to college?
Did you know that you were going to major in agriculture when you got there?
In what dormitory did you live when you got to A&M?
And can you share with me any of, do you recall any of the
What did the sophomores do to freshmen then?
There was never a lot of them.
Nobody said, you stand, you're sick today.
If you're sick or not, you're going to stay there.
So he stayed in the room.
There was one flag with the parking team that has the flag they gave us.
You said that they beat you some.
What would be the reason that a sophomore would give for whipping a freshman?
And you all ate in Cebiza.
You say the food was good.
What was your favorite Aggie food?
Anything that you could eat, I guess.
Did you come home for Thanksgiving?
But you didn't go to Houston or Dallas?
Did they make court trips then for football games?
And you went on the train?
When you when you went on the train, did you all get into any mischief?
Let's see, was Mr. Zachary one of your classmates?
And Harrington also described them as students.
Now, one of my favorite Aggie acquaintances was Buck Shewitz.
Tell me about your memory of him.
Buck Shewitz was a great fellow.
I wanted to go and study his little yard.
Father said, hey, no, it's going to buy a bunch of the yard.
So I'll study it and get that library.
So, they had a lot of go to L.A.M.
They'd give a doctor one-on-one with you.
You can't do it enough, sure.
Now, I noticed in the Longhorn, the yearbook, that Buck was the art editor.
Did you students think that Buck was a kind of a character?
What kind of goofy things did he do?
Anything that he wanted to do.
He was a very good student.
Now, did you become a collector of Shewitz art?
I know John Lindsay has a fine... Yes, sir.
Now, tell me when you get tired and we need to quit this.
What was some of your favorite courses that you took while you were a student?
A lot of them were good ones.
I decided I'd make good classes, good in this class.
I would, I'd, I'd, I'd, I'd, I'd, I'd, I'd,
Did you all do some field work then in agriculture?
Where were the field on the west campus?
When you were taking those courses, what kind of agriculture did you dream that you were going to practice?
Did you think you were going to be a rancher?
I guess I would be able to get those things.
Can you recall any of the pranks that you and your friends pulled off while you were students?
Did you fill anybody's room with water or trash?
Did you ever put an animal in anybody's room?
Because I've heard of some putting a heifer in somebody's room overnight, or a hog or something.
I remember going back to Goodboro.
I don't believe it's there anymore.
But it was one of the dorms where you lived?
I remember going out on my leg.
Now, where was the post office then?
How often did you get mail from home?
Did you write a letter home regularly?
Now, how did your family pay for you to go to A&M?
How often did you all hear news about the war in Europe?
I got her just... I got this card.
She said, oh, it's over there.
Because now, we got into the war at almost the same time you started as a student.
While the war was going on, did any of your close friends go to Europe and serve in the Army?
What did you and your friends do when you heard the war was over?
Where in Bryan did you, what was the name of, do you remember where in Bryan Aggies would celebrate?
Now, did those celebrations ever involve alcohol?
No, I didn't know anything about alcohol.
Was there a... I don't remember.
When you all were looking for a date, where did the young ladies live that you all dated?
How often did girlfriends come to College Station?
And they would come on the train?
Where did they spend the night?
That would be faculty, and did they charge anything for the girls to... Did you have a favorite faculty member that you... Who was it?
Did you all celebrate silver taps then?
